The tensile stress–strain tests and hysteresis loops were performed using a tensile tester (SANS EUT4103) with a 50 N load at a rate of 50 mm min−1 in the air at room temperature. The thickness, length and width of the hydrogel samples were set to 2, 50, and 10 mm, respectively, and the gauge length was set to 25 mm. The fracture energy was determined by employing the approach proposed by Rivlin et al. [47]. Specifically, two samples (15.0 mm wide, 2.0 mm thick) of the same hydrogel were pulled by the tensile tester, and the distance between the two clamps was 20 mm. Before testing, one sample was intact without notch, and the other was half-notched in width (the precise length of notch is not important for this measurement). Force-distance curves were subsequently obtained via stretching these two hydrogels at a rate of 50 mm min−1, and the area under the curve represents the work done by the applied force, W(L) (as illustrated in Fig. S1). Upon the notch turns into a running crack, the fracture energy can be accordingly calculated from Eq. 1:1Γ=WLca0×b0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
